'''''Joshua: Teenager vs. Superpower''''' is a 2017 documentary about [[Joshua Wong]], a teenager who rallies Hong Kong youth in dissent during the [[2014 Hong Kong Occupy Movement]] when the Chinese Communist Party reneged on its promise of autonomy to the territory. At Sundance, Netflix negotiated worldwide viewing rights for the documentary. The film premiered at the [[2017 Sundance Film Festival]] at the Park City Temple Theatre in Sundance's World Documentary Competition.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sundance-netflix-nabs-china-doc-joshua-teenager-superpower-967749 Sundance: Netflix Nabs China Doc 'Joshua: Teenager Vs. Superpower'], [[Hollywood Reporter]], by Tatiana Siegel, 23 Jan 2017</ref> The film was released on Netflix on 26 May 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/2092265/netflix-releases-trailer-documentary-about-hong-kong-pro|title=Netflix releases trailer for documentary about Hong Kong pro-democracy activist Joshua Wong|last=Singh|first=Harminder|date=2017-05-02|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=2017-05-02|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref>
==Awards and nominations== * World Cinema Audience Award in the 'Documentary' category at the 2017 Sundance Film Festival * [[Producers Guild of America Award]] (nominated)<ref>[https://www.hongkongfp.com/2018/10/20/matthew-tornes-last-exit-kai-tak-captures-underlying-betrayal-hong-kong-political-system/ Matthew Torne’s ‘Last Exit to Kai Tak’ captures the underlying betrayal of Hong Kong by its political system], [[Hong Kong Free Press|HKFP]], by Evan Fowler, 20 October 2018</ref>
